==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Persevere
<hw>Per`se*vere"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Persevered</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Persevering</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>pers⟦eacute⟧v⟦eacute⟧rer</ets>, L. <ets>perseverare</ets>, fr.
<ets>perseverus</ets> very strict; <ets>per + severus</ets> strict,
severe. See <er>Per-</er>, and <er>Severe</er>.]</ety> <def>To persist
in any business or enterprise undertaken; to pursue steadily any project
or course begun; to maintain a purpose in spite of counter influences,
opposition, or discouragement; not to give or abandon what is
undertaken.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thrice happy, if they know⟦br⟧
Their happiness, and <qex>persevere</qex> upright.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To <er>Persevere</er>, <er>Continue</er>,
<er>Persist</er>.</syn> <usage> The idea of not laying aside is common
to these words. <xex>Continue</xex> is the generic term, denoting simply
to do as one has done hitherto. To <xex>persevere</xex> is to
<xex>continue</xex> in a given course in spite of discouragements, etc.,
from a desire to obtain our end. To <xex>persist</xex> is to
<xex>continue</xex> from a determination of will not to give up.
<xex>Persist</xex> is frequently used in a bad sense, implying obstinacy
in pursuing an unworthy aim.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Persevering</ent>⟦br⟧
